  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n\n2. Regulatory Cooperation\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border investigations\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n3. Standardized Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence standards\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Coordinated asset seizure\n- Extradition agreements\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n\n5. Global Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Frameworks\n- Uniform definitions of money laundering\n- Consistent risk assessment protocols\n- Harmonized legal standards\n\n6. International Financial Institutions' Oversight\n- World Bank monitoring\n- IMF compliance assessments\n- Mutual evaluation processes\n\n7. Technology and Information Exchange\n- Shared digital platforms\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Collaborative intelligence networks\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive, multilayered approach to combating money laundering across national boundaries.",
